ame usually denotes a holder or owner of this amount of land, who would have been a prosperous small farmer and probably one of the leading men of his village. This surname is also found in other central European countries, for example Poland and Slovenia. See also   Hoffner  , compare   Hueber  .","Dutch: variant of   Hubert  ."]}]},{"name":"Francis","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of Italian Francesco , originally a vocabulary word meaning ‘French’ or ‘Frenchman’ (Late Latin <i>Franciscus</i>;  compare  Frank  ). This was a nickname given to  St Francis  of Assisi (  1181–1226 ) because of his wealthy father's business connections with France. His baptismal name was  Giovanni . He had a pleasant, ordinary life as a child and young man, but after two serious illnesses, a period of military service, and a year as a prisoner of war in Perugia, he turned from the world and devoted himself to caring for the poor and sick. He was joined by groups of disciples, calling themselves ‘minor friars’ (<i>friari minores</i>). The main features of the Franciscan rule are humility, poverty, and love for all living creatures. The given name occurs occasionally in England as early as  1300 , and more frequently from the early 16th century, when there was a surge of admiration for, and imitation of, Italian Renaissance culture."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Jean","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Like   Jane   and   Joan  , a medieval variant of Old French <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Towards the end of the Middle Ages this form became largely confined to Scotland. In the 20th century it became more widely used in the English-speaking world and enjoyed a period of great popularity, but it is now out of fashion. Among numerous well-known and influential bearers are the British novelists  Jean Plaidy  (  Eleanor Hibbert ,  1910–93 ) and  Jean Rhys  (  Ella Gwendolen Rees Williams ,  1894–1979 ), British actress  Jean Simmons  (  1929–2010 ), and American-born actress  Jean Seberg  (  1938–79 ). It is also found as a variant spelling of the masculine name   Gene ."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]},{"name":"Jeane","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jean ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Francis Jean Hoover was born in 1265, in Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Hoover. She had at least 2 sons with Robert de Tyndale II. She died in 1325, in her hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1265–1325":"1265–1325","1250–1293":"1250–1293","1285–Male":"1285–Surnud","1292–1332":"1292–1332","–Male":"Surnud","Est 1285":"umbes 1285","1325":"1325","1332":"1332","1265":"1265","1285":"1285","1250":"1250","1293":"1293","1292":"1292","Northampton, England":"Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Oundle, Ashton, Northampton, England":"Oundle, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom",", , Northampton, England, United Kingdom":"Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Tansor, Oundle, Northamptonshire, England":"Tansor, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1265–1325":"1265–1325","1250–1293":"1250–1293","1285–Male":"1285–Kuollut","1292–1332":"1292–1332","–Male":"Kuollut","Est 1285":"noin 1285","1325":"1325","1332":"1332","1265":"1265","1285":"1285","1250":"1250","1293":"1293","1292":"1292","Northampton, England":"Northamptonshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Oundle, Ashton, Northampton, England":"Oundle, Northamptonshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta",", , Northampton, England, United Kingdom":"Northamptonshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Tansor, Oundle, Northamptonshire, England":"Tansor, Northamptonshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1265–1325":"1265–1325","1250–1293":"1250–1293","1285–Male":"1285–Décédé","1292–1332":"1292–1332","–M